Like Mr Sutton, the American was wearing a wingsuit when he jumped from the top of a 2500 meter cliff near the summit of Brevent.

He got into difficulties on the way down, and his lifeless body was later found by mountain rescuers. 

The accident has increased calls for the authorities to reinstate a ban on wingsuits – jumpsuits made of a special fabric which increase the surface area of the body, so allowing users ‘to fly’ after launching themselves from a mountainside or high building, or from a plane.

The idea is that sportsmen can enjoy the feeling of flying before opening a parachute and landing. Mr Sutton, who was Daniel Craig’s double in the hugely popular Olympic stunt, died when he hit a ridge near the Swiss town of Martigny, Switzerland, close to the French border in August.

